      excerpt: 'Plus, another episode of Trump v. Todd Young.',
      summary:
        "Apologies for my hiatus last week. I took a week away from my work devices after that marathon 24-hour end to the legislative session.\nIn the meantime, if you're on Twitter as much as I am, you might have noticed a significant uptick in tweets from some statewide electoral hopefuls. Once the General Assembly adjourns their session, it's free reign to begin soliciting campaign donations. The 2024 election is right around the corner!\nLoad Error\nLet's catch up.\n\nForwarded this letter from a friend? Sign up for Hoosier Politics here.\nAttention HamCo and beyond: Indiana's 5th Congressional District race is shaping up. Yes, the election still a year and a half away.\nU.S. Rep. Victoria Spartz has already said she won't run again, nor does she have plans to run for Mike Braun's U.S. Senate seat opening up. No one's yet raised their hand to run against U.S. Rep. Jim Banks for Braun's seat. Braun is running for governor.\nNoblesville state Rep. Chuck Goodrich and Madison County Prosecutor Rodney Cummings have launched campaigns for Spartz's seat within the last couple weeks. Goodrich, CEO of Gaylor Electric, has already loaned himself $1 million. Read about them here.\nFormer state schools superintendent Jennifer McCormick is the first Democrat to enter the race for Indiana governor.\nThough she only flipped parties in 2021, the Indiana GOP has considered her a Democrat since 2020, when she started endorsing a slew of Democratic candidates ― including opponents to House Speaker Todd Huston and Gov. Eric Holcomb.\nIndiana hasn't had a Democratic governor since 2005, when Joe Kernan served out the remainder of the late Frank O'Bannon's second term.\nHolcomb can't run again due to term limits. On the Republican ticket so far are Lt. Gov. Suzanne Crouch, U.S. Sen. Mike Braun and Fort Wayne businessman Eric Doden. Donald Rainwater is running as a libertarian.\nBraun and Doden are neck-and-neck on fundraising: $2.9 million and $2.8 million in their coffers, respectively.\nQuick recaps from the municipal primary:\n\nThe legislature hit on a lot of big topics this session, from education spending to transgender youth to health care affordability.\nBut if you're wondering, how exactly is my life going to change? Cate Charron and I put that list together.\nAnd as a quick follow-up, she got the deets about a new highway speed camera program lawmakers approved.\nIndiana's Republican U.S. Sen. Todd Young did not get President Donald Trump's endorsement for reelection in 2022. Now he's dishing it back.\nOn CNN Thursday, Young said he will not support Trump for the Republican presidential nomination. Asked why, he said, \"Where do I begin?\"\nReminder: Young famously bucked Trump by saying, before the Capitol attack, he was voting to certify the Electoral College results on Jan. 6.\nIt may be a stretch to include this in a political letter, but hey, it's hundreds of millions of tax dollars, and we're happy it's done.\nNow that the I-65/I-70 North Split interchange in downtown Indianapolis is open, \"beautification\" can begin. At 1 p.m. today, local officials will plant ceremonial trees on the site of the future \"urban forest\" near the interchange off Lewis Street.\n-SEND US YOUR FEEDBACK-\nHoosier Politics is compiled and written by the IndyStar politics and government team. Send us tips or let us know what you think of the letter by emailing kdwyer@IndyStar.com.\nThis article originally appeared on Indianapolis Star: Primary post-op | 2024 races\nLike us on Facebook to see similar stories\nPlease give an overall site rating:",
