      title: 'Communities roll out plans for Bike to Work Day, Week',
      author: 'Journal Record Staff',
      published_date: '2023-05-12 14:15:00',
      published_date_precision: 'timezone unknown',
      link: 'https://journalrecord.com/2023/05/12/communities-roll-out-plans-for-bike-to-work-day-week/',
      clean_url: 'journalrecord.com',
      excerpt:
        'As Oklahoma coasts toward warm weather season, people might want to dust off bikes and helmets and air up tires to participate in National Bike Month.',
      summary:
        "Oklahoma City, Edmond, Norman, Piedmont, Yukon and Guthrie are among communities in Oklahoma that have promoted May as National Bike Month, including plans for people to take part in National Bike to Work Day on May 19. (Photo by Marianna Lutkova on Unsplash)\n \nAs Oklahoma coasts toward warm weather season, people might want to dust off bikes and helmets and air up tires to participate in National Bike Month.\n\n\nBike to Work Week will roll in on May 15 and continue through May 21. For those who would like to take part, but maybe only for a day, National Bike to Work Day has been set for May 19.\n\n\nAccording to local officials, Oklahoma City, Edmond, Norman, Piedmont, Yukon and Guthrie are among communities in the Sooner State that have launched plans for group rides or other events.\n\n\nThere will be no fewer than five organized group rides in Oklahoma City on the morning of May 19, beginning in the Plaza District, Mesta Park, at the 30th Street Market, in the Wheeler District, and at the Oklahoma Science Museum. All five routes will end at Bicentennial Park downtown, where riders and others will convene between 7:45 a.m. and 9 a.m. to swap stories and enjoy free drinks provided by Junction Coffee.\n\n\n'Looking for a group ride? Join one of many group rides from various neighborhoods around the metro. Or, rally your local bicycling community and start your own group ride and meet us downtown at Bicentennial Park,' the city said in a news release.\n\n\nFind out more online at \nacogok.org/bikecentral\n.\n\n\nSunday, May 21, is Bike to Place of Worship Day.\n\n\nOrganizers say the overriding goal of Bike Month is to educate people young and old about benefits of bicycling, while also teaching safe riding practices and promoting resources available to cyclists. In central Oklahoma, it's hosted by the Association of Central Oklahoma Governments. The city of Oklahoma City is a major supporter and sponsor.\n\n\nNotably, the city is beginning to reap benefits of a large, multi-year investment in bike lanes and other bike infrastructure as part of its ongoing 'active transportation' community plan. It also has invested in an educational campaign, including outreach events designed to help ensure the safety not only of bicyclists but also pedestrians. Details can be found at watchformeok.org.\n\n\nThe educational campaign was planned in tandem with a project phase, which included installation of more than 10 miles of bicycle facilities on N. Shartel Avenue, Exchange Avenue, Westwood Boulevard, N. 13th Street, NW Fourth Street and W. Sheridan Avenue. Goals were to make the streets safer and more accessible to bicyclists and pedestrians.\n\n\n'By the end of May, several of the new bike facilities will have been installed and will be available for bicyclists to enjoy during Bike Month and beyond,' the city said.\n\nd",
