      title: 'Kansas Vietnam vet pays respects to brothers at traveling memorial wall',
      author: '',
      published_date: '2023-05-12 14:15:00',
      published_date_precision: 'timezone unknown',
      link: 'https://www.kake.com/story/48896367/kansas-vietnam-vet-pays-respects-to-brothers-at-traveling-memorial-wall',
      clean_url: 'kake.com',
      excerpt:
        "The Wall that Heals has come to Kansas. It's a traveling Vietnam Veterans Memorial replica that travels around the county.",
      summary:
        "GREAT BEND, Kan. (KAKE) - The Wall That Heals has come to Kansas. It's a traveling Vietnam veterans memorial replica that travels around the county.\nThis time it's in Great Bend. KAKE News spoke to a man who visited the memorial to pay respects to his friends.\n\"That's Narciso Francis Herrera, and David, Weston David MacLean,' said Brad Hancock, a Vietnam War vet.\nVietnam Vet Brad Hancock is referring to two of his late friends who served in the war with him. He calls his two friends his brothers, and they're the real heroes in his eyes.\n\"These guys were 19 and 20 years old. And they didn't get a chance at life. This means they keep on living in a sense. They certainly continue to be with me,' said Hancock.\nHancock, seeing his two brothers' names reflects on how much life they missed out on by serving our county, giving the ultimate sacrifice.\n\"Nineteen or 20 you haven't gotten married, you haven't had any kids, you haven't had many jobs. You're in the marine corps, and you're in the infantry and you find yourself in the jungle and in combat,' said Hancock. \nThe Memorial Wall, a replica of the one in Washington D.C. is something Hancock hasn't seen in 40 years. The last time he saw the Memorial Wall was in California. Despite not seeing the one in D.C., the replica brings back memories of his time in Vietnam.\n\"Right here, Weston David MacLean, and he was killed on July 20th when we walked into an ambush together. And unfortunately, he didn't make it out. They were my friends. And so I'm glad to see they live on through this wall,' said Hancock.\nThe wall will be up 24 hours a day until 2 p.m. on Sunday, May 14th in Veterans Memorial Park.",
