      title: 'Salmon-Thirty-Salmon Livery Is Back At Alaska Airlines With An Indigenous Twist',
      author: 'Luke Peters',
      published_date: '2023-05-12 14:15:00',
      published_date_precision: 'timezone unknown',
      link: 'https://www.msn.com/en-us/travel/news/salmon-thirty-salmon-livery-is-back-at-alaska-airlines-with-an-indigenous-twist/ar-AA1b6bP6',
      clean_url: 'msn.com',
      excerpt: 'The stunning new paint scheme is a fine replacement for its highly-regarded predecessor.',
      summary:
        "has unveiled an eye-catching new livery for one of its aircraft, replacing the much-loved and recently retired 'Salmon-Thirty-Salmon II' scheme on the same airframe. The new livery celebrates Alaskan indigenous peoples, their language, and their culture.\n has just unveiled its newest aircraft paint theme. Replacing the much-loved 'Salmon Thirty-Salmon II' scheme, which was retired just last month, the same airframe has now appeared from the company's hangar sporting an all-new design but still based on the same water-borne creature.\nThe new color scheme, named 'Xáat Kwáani,' was designed by the talented Alaska Native artist Crystal Kaakeeyáa Rose Demientieff Worl. Xáat Kwáani means 'Salmon People' in the Alaskan Tlingit language and refers to the spiritual link between the people who interact with the beloved salmon and all those who benefit from the species' stewardship of the environment.\nUsing a design technique known as Northwest Coast formline art, the salmon design by Worl is a one-of-a-kind work that honors salmon, culture, artistic expression, and language. Traditional formline art dates back thousands of years and is a two-dimensional design style of the Northwest Coast.\nAccording to an official  statement, as a tribute to the Xáat Kwáani people, the special Boeing 737-800 (tail number N559AS) is the first of any US domestic airline fleet to be named in an Alaska Native language and to depict the ancestral importance of salmon through Northwest Coast formline art.\nThe livery on the recently repainted aircraft also represents the first time  has featured a language besides English on the fuselage of any of its aircraft.\nThe Boeing 737 has been completely stripped of its previous salmon-based scheme and is now resplendent in a combination of blue shades. Depicted across the entire fuselage length is the stylized image of a complete salmon in white, with a further salmon diving down the vertical stabilizer.\nThe eye-catching scheme is highlighted with splashes of pink on various specific points of the salmon imagery and is finished off with small 'Alaska' titles along the window line, rear of the wing. The winglets also replicate the stylized salmon image depicted on the tail.\nFurther facts about the new livery are that it took 117 gallons of paint to complete the livery, with the four main colors being Midnight Blue, Atlas Blue, White, and Pink. From landing to take-off, it took just 12 days to paint, and the special livery will fly for several years through a paint system that applies a protective clear coat over the base coats.\nHere is a short timelapse video that depicts the complete repainting process of N559AS into its new scheme.\nUnveiling the new color scheme, Marilyn Romano, Regional Vice-President of , said\nCrystal Worl has a love of monumental art - most recently, murals gracing the sides of buildings in Juneau and Anchorage for locals and visitors to enjoy. And we had a large blank canvas with a 737-800. During our first conversation, Crystal shared her desire to paint an  plane, as she has flown with us most of her life. Salmon as a focus was intentional, and Crystal shares the relationship between salmon and Native people through storytelling and artistic design.'\nCrystal Kaakeeyáa Rose Demientieff Worl is Tlingit Athabascan from Raven moiety, LukaaxÌ±.ádi Sockeye Clan, from the Raven House and is Deg Hit'an Athabascan (on her mother's side) from Fairbanks, Alaska, and Filipino. Through her art, Worl aims to bring attention to Indigenous culture and to pass on ancestral values to a new generation.\nSpeaking about her involvement in the project, Worl said,\n'Every time I looked at an Alaska plane, I couldn't help but visualize the salmon being in formline, or having some sort of design that represents identity. I can't help but look at things and see how to Indigenize them. I have high hopes this project will encourage people to learn and embrace Indigenous culture and values.'\nWorl has previously created several public art installations in Alaska, including a design on the side of a Juneau fire/rescue ambulance, a steel cut medallion installed in downtown Juneau, and a 60-foot by 25-foot mural of Tlingit activist Elizabeth Peratrovich on Juneau's downtown library building.\nLast year, Worl painted a mural 125-foot by 48-foot in Anchorage. In March 2023, Worl was commissioned to design 'The Art of Skateboarding' series of postal stamps for the United States Postal Service that celebrated the sport of skateboarding and what Indigenous groups have brought to the skating culture.\nWorl is a resident of Juneau, Alaska, as a co-owner and co-designer of a design company with her brother. The company (Trickster Company) promotes innovative Indigenous design focused on the Northwest Coast art and exploring themes and issues in Native culture.\nIn the video below, Worl explains more about her cultural heritage, how she designed the new livery and the significance and importance of the salmon held by the indigenous populations of Alaska.\nAccording to data from ch-aviation.com, the aircraft featuring the new scheme (N559AS) was initially delivered to  in August 2006. Like the other 59  Boeing 737-800s, it carries 159 passengers in a three-class configuration, with 12 seats in first class, 30 in premium class, and 117 in economy class.\nFresh out of the paint bay, the aircraft will begin flying later today (May 12th, 2023) with an inaugural flight from Anchorage (ANC) through Southeast Alaska. The first stop of  flight 62 will be through Worl's hometown of Juneau, the state's capital, before continuing through Sitka, Ketchikan, and onward to its final destination of Seattle-Tacoma International Airport (SEA).\nAfter  announced earlier this year that it would soon be retiring the 'Salmon Thirty Salmon II' livery on N559AS, over 2,000 aviation enthusiasts signed a petition asking  to keep its iconic special livery, but to no avail.\nHowever, the airline revealed that it would soon unveil the aircraft's new livery, which it said would \"celebrates the culture and people of Alaska and our connection to the places we fly.\"\nThe airline will be hoping that those 2,000 petitionees (and others) will be pleased with the aircraft's latest stunning transformation.\nWhat are your thoughts on the new color scheme? Do you prefer it to the 'Salmon-Thirty-Salmon II' scheme previously worn by the same plane? Let us know in the comments.\nSource: ch-aviation.com\nLike us on Facebook to see similar stories\nPlease give an overall site rating:",
